english:
  title: A Letter Presented to Councillor Yun Wi
  author: Lee Gyeo-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On [this] day and month, your humble servant bows twice and respectfully submits this brief letter to the honored seat of the Celestial Ministry's Councillor.

    I was once a student in the household of Minister He, the noble of Hadong. Among a thousand candidates, I alone was elevated to the first rank—a mark of exceptional favor indeed. As you have become the Minister's son-in-law through marriage, you should regard me as a younger brother. Moreover, you should know how the Minister has treated me from beginning to end, and so I speak without hesitation.

    When the Minister held great office, he delighted in promoting rising talents. Many scholars drank from his generous fountain and were touched by his grace. Yet I alone, dwelling in his household, received none of these gifts—not through his fault, but through my own doing. In my youth, I gave myself to wine and excess, earning the name of a madman. The Minister wished to advance me, yet seeing this reputation for madness, he withheld his hand, thinking perhaps that youth and unbridled spirit were to blame, and that in time I would reform and his patronage would not come too late.

    When later I fell ill and sought to retire, only after I had written three memorials did the Minister shower me with praise and affection, declaring that I was no madman at all, and expressing regret that he had not employed me earlier. He wrote strong recommendations to the throne itself. Yet the king too had heard of my madness and refused to use me. And so I have languished until this day. If even the Minister of Rites suffered such fate, what of lesser men? From the highest officials to common friends, all have marked me with the name of madman. Unable to bear the judgment of the people, I have even taken to calling myself "the mad wanderer."

    Yet this madness is no empty name—it has substance. When a great man possesses talent yet cannot exercise it, when knowledge burns within him yet finds no outlet, his spirit grows turbulent, like water trapped in winding channels, churning and roaring with nowhere to escape. It is only when wine loosens him that this spirit erupts from his chest to his throat like a bursting levee—the waters overflow and rush without restraint until they have spent themselves completely. This is the nature of my madness.

    But mark this: such madness comes only from the frustration of disappointed men who turn to wine. It is not like the madness of one whom illness has seized. Should a man suddenly gain position and fortune, should official rank and renown bind him with bridle and rein, then though you urge him a hundred times to be mad, he would refuse. Why? For this is the way of men: in poverty they care little for life, and in success they guard their safety carefully. How much more so with a scholar who has transformed himself from madness to wisdom—is he not the very instrument to achieve great things?

    Consider the horse. In a man's house, horses that are tame and gentle, though occasionally a remarkable breed appears, rarely show feet swift enough to follow clouds and outrace the sun. But those born and raised in mountain forests and island wilds—when they see a man they bolt like startled deer, impossible to catch quickly. Even when captured, they cannot be easily mastered. Fortune may bind them and bring them to a stable, yet they gnaw on trees and refuse grain, knowing it not. When ridden, they dash toward ravines and plunge into streams until the rider falls senseless. But let time pass, and gradually they grow accustomed to man. Apply the bridle and rein repeatedly, train the gait with patience, and soon they will possess hooves swift enough to travel a thousand li. Did not the Han Emperor say: "The unbridled horse and the unbound scholar—both require only proper guidance"? So it is.

    Alas! While the whole realm branded me a madman, when you beheld me and we shared but one conversation, you perceived my true nature. You treated me as a man of noble character and lamented that our meeting came so late. Each time I visited your threshold, you would greet me barefoot in welcome, seizing my hand and pressing close. Morning would fade to dusk unnoticed; evening would stretch into night. Though sometimes wine would make me cry out wildly, you never deemed it madness. Instead you said: "This man is not truly mad—he simply possesses talent that finds no use, knowledge with nowhere to pour forth, and that is the source of his affliction."

    Not even the trust between Bao Shu and Guan Zhong, nor the wordless understanding between Bo Ya and Ziqi, could exceed such recognition! In this way, what you have shown me is intimate and devoted—heart speaking to heart, spirit communing with spirit.

    Now, by fortune, you have been entrusted with the celestial ministry's oversight of appointments. It seems you might raise me up. Were I truly mad, I would rest assured in my heart, presume upon our old friendship, and make bold claims without hesitation. And should misfortune strike and things not turn in my favor, I would harbor resentment and betray all the tender care and devoted regard you have shown me.

    But I am not so. Weighing this humbly in my heart, I see clearly that you are merely an officer of the celestial ministry, not its master nor holder of its authority. You can only speak softly to the Chancellor who holds real power, and nothing more. If the moment does not arise, what is to be done? If you speak and are not heard, what remedy is there? Success or failure rests in a single moment—it is all the decree of Heaven. How dare I say more?
